item_39","output":"ID:       ddx-11f01241\nTitle:    agent: close parent after post-attempt decomposition\nType:     task\nStatus:   open\nPriority: 0\nLabels:   area:agent, area:bead-lifecycle, area:decomposition, kind:bug, kind:correctness, phase:iterate, prevention, related:ddx-130cf9ab, spec:FEAT-010, spec:TD-031\nParent:   ddx-e9542e0d\nDesc:     PROBLEM\nThe post-attempt recovery/decomposer path applies the same park-open decomposition pattern as pre-claim intake. A successful lossless post-attempt split should close the decomposed parent while leaving generated children work-ready; it should not strand an open execution-ineligible parent.\n\nROOT CAUSE WITH FILE:LINE\n- cli/internal/agent/recovery_decompose.go:130-133 documents that a successful decomposition creates child beads, sets `execution-eligible=false`, and emits `decompose-applied`.\n- cli/internal/agent/recovery_decompose.go:207-210 updates the parent extra metadata to `execution-eligible=false` after child creation instead of closing the parent through the lifecycle/store API.\n- cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_intake_decompose_test.go currently covers post-attempt too-large no_changes decomposition with old open/ineligible expectations.\n- cli/internal/agent/recovery_decompose_test.go:20-22 says the post-ladder decomposer creates child beads and sets parent `execution-eligible=false`, locking in the old lifecycle.\n\nPROPOSED FIX\n- Update `runDecomposer` in cli/internal/agent/recovery_decompose.go so successful lossless decomposition closes the parent through the lifecycle/store API after child beads are created.\n- Preserve durable `decompose-applied` evidence with generated child IDs and cost/route fields already recorded by the path.\n- Clear parent claim metadata and heartbeat fields on the closed parent.\n- Ensure post-attempt generated children use `Parent=\u003cdecomposed-id\u003e` as hierarchy metadata only and are not blocked by a dependency on the decomposed parent.\n- Update post-attempt and post-ladder tests to assert close semantics, child readiness, and `decompose-applied` child ID evidence.\n\nNON-SCOPE\n- Do not change pre-claim intake decomposition or auto-epic decomposition in this bead; those are separate children under ddx-e9542e0d.\n- Do not implement ddx-130cf9ab's broader doctor/back-edge repair work.\n- Do not redesign historical `dead_intermediate_close` behavior for already-open containers.\n\nPARENT AND DEPS\nParent: ddx-e9542e0d.\nDeps: No deps.\nAccept:   1. `runDecomposer` in `cli/internal/agent/recovery_decompose.go` closes the decomposed parent through the lifecycle/store API after generated child beads are created.\n2. `decompose-applied` evidence still includes generated child IDs and existing cost/route metadata.\n3. Parent claim metadata and heartbeat fields are cleared on the closed decomposed parent.\n4. `TestPostAttemptTooLargeNoChanges_ClosesParentAndLeavesChildrenReady` proves post-attempt orchestrator decomposition closes the parent and generated children remain ready through the `Parent` field when they have no explicit deps.\n5. `TestPostLadderExhaustion_TriggersDecompose_ReviewTooLarge_ClosesParent` proves the post-ladder decomposer path closes the parent and records `decompose-applied` with child IDs.\n6. `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./internal/agent/... ./internal/bead/... -run 'PostAttemptTooLargeNoChanges|PostLadderExhaustion_TriggersDecompose|DecomposeDoesNotSelfDep|parent_ancestor_in_deps' -count=1` passes.\n7. `lefthook run pre-commit` passes.\nCreated:  2026-06-17 19:59:30\nUpdated:  2026-06-17 19:59:30\nspec-id: FEAT-010\n"}}
